Flattening the World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman says so.  Friedman chose this title for his bestselling book to make readers realize the amazing impact of technology on the global economy.
Distances are shrinking.
Geographic barriers can no longer provide easy protection.
Europe's manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals face the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they are talking to may be thousands of miles away in India.
Skeptics pointed out the limitations of the Friedman analogy.
As someone said, the world is not flat, but rather "uneven".
The contour map of global economic activities shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Not only that, the distance has not yet lost its effect.
Even in neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, domestic trade far exceeds cross-border trade.
Although Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, Vancouver's trade with Toronto, which is farther away, far exceeds that with nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticism, Friedman still raised an important point.
Globalization can be defined as the interdependence between different continents, its history as long as that of humanity, witnessing the migration of races and religions, and witnessing the ancient Silk Road trade along the route between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different, with a faster pace of development and a much deeper level of penetration.
After the first transatlantic telegraph cable was completed in 1868, Europeans and Americans could exchange information in just a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes painted a picture of British people living in London using the phone to order goods from around the world, and then waiting at home for delivery in the afternoon.
However, Keynes' British people belonged to the exception of being extremely wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world at local supermarkets.
Similar situations occurred 20 years ago with instant global communication, but it was beyond the reach of most people in terms of cost.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an internet cafe and gain the ability that was only accessible to governments, multinational companies, and a few individuals or institutions with a large budget in the past.
The significant decrease in the costs of computation, communication, and transportation has made technology more accessible to the general public.
Just 10 years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, the proportion of internet users in the United States is less than one-fourth of the global total.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have mastered information has set a new record in human history.
Non-governmental organizations now possess the capabilities that were previously only possessed by governments.
The status of nation-states as the main subjects of world politics will not change for the time being, but they must learn to share this vast stage with more participants, including institutions such as the Oxford Famine Relief Committee, celebrities such as Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like Al-Qaeda.
However, this flattening process is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred in the past.
1914 year the world economy was highly integrated, but the following 30 years, the economic dependence between countries continued to decline.
It wasn't until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had previously experienced, and at that time it was still heavily separated by the Iron Curtain.
World War I was the spark that triggered the reversal, during World War II and the Cold War, people witnessed the decline of economic globalization and the rise of military globalization.
This reflects the deeper underlying problems of domestic inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, and the result was the abnormal ideological trends, fascism and communism at their peak, the pathological development ideas led to the fragmentation of the country and the world.
After World War II, the Western welfare state system has provided a safety net for people who suffered in economic changes, encouraging them to accept the rewards brought by international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that the role played by China today is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic unrest, constantly moving towards nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and ultimately triggering a world war that reverses the progress of economic globalization.
Although the US and China's economies are highly interdependent today, what about the economies of Britain and Germany before 1914?
Such reasoning is, however, imperfect.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of the UK.
However, even if China maintains its current high growth rate, it is unlikely to catch up with the US in at least 20 years.
The threat to the flat world is more likely to come from non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
In 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in a surprise attack on September 11 than the Japanese government did in the 1941 Pearl Harbor attack.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such a force has nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world will undergo a revolution.
At that time, personnel and goods crossing the border will become more difficult.
If the above force destroys the oil output of the Persian Gulf, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic recession like that of the 1930s can further strengthen the power of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two main driving forces of globalization.
So far, policy has further consolidated the effect of technological flatness.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States holds a leading position in driving policy to eliminate obstacles.
The events described above may reverse this policy.
Some global critics may be willing to see this result.
But such a result, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situation in two fields - the economic globalization trend of spreading technology and power would reverse, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization would be further consolidated, such as wars, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If so, the flat world will become a desert.
